      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Commercial FEA solver (Ansys) with documented QA procedures and version control satisfies Gradation 2 for Class II device context.",
      "rationale": "Ansys Mechanical 2022 R2 used with documented installation qualification, regression test suite, and version-locked solver settings. QA records archived in DePuy Synthes PLM system. Gradation 2 requirements satisfied."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Benchmark problems with known analytical solutions demonstrate solver correctness for linear static structural analysis.",
      "rationale": "Three NAFEMS benchmark problems (LE1, LE3, LE10) executed in the deployed solver configuration; results within 1% of reference solutions. Code verification complete for the element types and boundary conditions used in the pedicle screw model."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Mesh convergence study demonstrates QoI change <2% between successive refinements.",
      "rationale": "Three-level mesh refinement study performed (coarse 1.5 mm, medium 0.8 mm, fine 0.4 mm global seed). Stiffness QoI changed 3.1% coarse-to-medium and 0.7% medium-to-fine; Richardson extrapolation GCI = 1.2%. Fine mesh adopted for all production runs."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Iterative solver residuals below 1e-6; nonlinear equilibrium residuals below 0.1% of reaction force.",
      "rationale": "Sparse direct solver (SPARSE) used for linear substeps; force convergence criterion 0.05% applied throughout nonlinear loading ramp. All 11 construct simulations converged within 200 substeps with no divergence events logged."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Documented modeling protocol and independent peer review of simulation setup reduce use-error risk to acceptable level.",
      "rationale": "Standardized modeling protocol document (MPD-001 Rev C) governs geometry import, material assignment, contact definition, and boundary condition application. An independent analyst reviewed and approved all 11 simulation setups prior to execution. No discrepancies identified."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Model physics (linear elastic with contact nonlinearity) is appropriate for the loading regime and QoIs of interest; literature precedent supports model form selection.",
      "rationale": "Linear elastic constitutive models for titanium alloy (Ti-6Al-4V) and UHMWPE vertebral body surrogate are well-established for quasi-static compression-bending below yield. Frictional contact (mu=0.2) at screw-rod interface captures load transfer mechanics consistent with published ASTM F1717 FEA literature. Model form assessed as appropriate for the COU."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Material properties and geometric inputs sourced from traceable measurements or certified material data; sensitivity analysis confirms QoI insensitivity to input uncertainty within reported ranges.",
      "rationale": "Ti-6Al-4V elastic modulus (114 GPa) and yield strength (880 MPa) taken from ASTM F136 certificate of conformance for the production lot. UHMWPE surrogate modulus (1.0 GPa) measured by DMA on representative coupons (CV=4%). One-at-a-time sensitivity analysis shows stiffness QoI varies <3% across ±2 SD input ranges. Inputs assessed as adequate."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "N≥10 production-representative specimens tested; dimensional inspection confirms geometric conformance; lot traceability documented.",
      "rationale": "Eleven (N=11) production-intent non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs assembled from a single production lot (Lot 2021-NC-07). Dimensional inspection of 5 randomly selected screws confirmed rod-screw interface geometry within drawing tolerances. Lot traceability records retained. Sample size exceeds the pre-specified minimum of N=10."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test conditions span the range of clinically relevant loading scenarios or are demonstrably bounding; at minimum, two distinct test configurations evaluated.",
      "rationale": "All validation experiments were conducted under a single ASTM F1717 standard test configuration (40 mm offset, quasi-static ramp at 5 mm/min, ambient temperature). While this configuration is the regulatory standard and represents a well-defined worst-case geometry, the validation evidence is limited to this single condition. Engineering judgment supports that ASTM F1717 is conservative relative to in vivo loading; however, no additional test configurations (e.g., varied offset distances or dynamic loading) were included to substantiate the bounding claim."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Model boundary conditions and loading replicate test fixture geometry and applied loads to within measurement uncertainty.",
      "rationale": "Test fixture geometry (ASTM F1717 standard fixture) digitized via CMM and imported directly into the FEA pre-processor. Applied displacement ramp in simulation matches test machine crosshead displacement profile. Fixture compliance measured (0.3 N/mm) and incorporated as a spring boundary condition. Equivalency of input parameters confirmed."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison metric (E/uval) applied to all three QoIs; E/uval < 1.96 for each QoI constitutes passing.",
      "rationale": "E/uval computed per ASME V&V 40 Section 5.4 for stiffness (E/uval=0.91), yield force (E/uval=1.42), and force at 40 mm (E/uval=1.18). All three QoIs satisfy the pre-specified acceptance criterion of E/uval < 1.96. Percentage differences are 4.2%, 7.8%, and 6.3% respectively, all within the 10% bound. Output comparison factor assessed as meeting requirements."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs used in validation are the same quantities used in the COU prediction; clinical relevance of QoIs is documented.",
      "rationale": "Construct stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement are the three QoIs specified in the COU and are the quantities extracted from both FEA and experimental data. These QoIs are directly referenced in FDA guidance for spinal implant mechanical testing. Relevance confirmed."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation experiments use the same device design, loading mode, and test standard as the COU; any differences are documented and assessed.",
      "rationale": "Validation activity uses production-intent non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screws under ASTM F1717 compression-bending, which is exactly the COU configuration. Both laboratories (Lab A: FDA CDRH, Lab B: DePuy Synthes) used the same standard fixture. No differences between validation and COU configurations were identified. Relevance of validation activities assessed as fully adequate."
    }
  ],
